data.content:
Yes — you can use **tuples** to get type safety while keeping it concise:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Why this is better:**
- **Type-safe** — compiler catches mismatches (no silent `object` boxing)
- **Named fields** — self-documenting test data
- **Same `[DynamicData]` attribute** — no other changes needed

> **Note:** Tuple support in `[DynamicData]` requires **MSTest v3.8+**. If you're on an older version, the `object[]` approach or `[DataRow]` for simple cases are your options:

```csharp
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
[TestMethod]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

`[DataRow]` works great for inline constant values. Use `[DynamicData]` with tuples when you need computed or non-constant test data.
